<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-528-470  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 528 470.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  August 1989 v18 n10 p42(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Data stream dreams: IBM moves toward a universal terminal. (newspecifications; includes related article on definition of datastreams)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lowe, Sue J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM is considering revamping its 'data stream' specifications andis briefing communications consultants on possible changes.andP;  Datastreams define how data will be formatted for terminal and printeroutput, and differing streams cause incompatibilities betweenterminals and multiple hosts.andP;  IBM is attempting to define asingle data-stream specification in order to create a 'universal'workstation which can talk to all hosts, minicomputers, andservers.andP;  Any changes in the company's specifications are likelyto have a profound impact on third-party vendors ofterminal-emulation products and file-transfer software.andP;  Vendorsnote that intelligent terminal support is a particularly importantissue.andP;  The huge installed base of protocol-specific equipmentposes many standardization difficulties, and many observers expectthe company to either keep its two data streams separate orabandon both entirely.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (planning).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Data CommunicationsProtocolSAASpecificationsConnectivityData ManagementTerminal Emulation.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   SAA's data streams. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>